<div id="review_580162154" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/580162154" />
    <a title="Russell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/739602-russell"><img alt="Russell" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/580162154?book_show_action=true">Apr 03, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Russell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Russell" href="/user/show/739602-russell">Russell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer580162154" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8260904858383079996">Before I started reading this book I was afraid that it might be more an anti-religion tirade than a history book. I&apos;m happy to say that my assumption was unfounded. Jacoby&apos;s history of secularism in America is well researched, mostly unbiased, and nicely written. When she occasionally strays away from straight history and into editorialism, her thoughts are well thought out and soundly argued. It isn&apos;t until the final chapter, however, that she really steps completely out of history and into pe</span>
  <span id="freeText8260904858383079996" style="display:none">Before I started reading this book I was afraid that it might be more an anti-religion tirade than a history book. I'm happy to say that my assumption was unfounded. Jacoby's history of secularism in America is well researched, mostly unbiased, and nicely written. When she occasionally strays away from straight history and into editorialism, her thoughts are well thought out and soundly argued. It isn't until the final chapter, however, that she really steps completely out of history and into personal commentary. This chapter might not be for everyone. However, I think think all Americans, no matter what their personal beliefs, would learn a lot from this book and find it fascinating, as I did.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8260904858383079996" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
