<div id="review_875039301" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/875039301" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3506592-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1458348049p2/3506592.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/875039301?book_show_action=true">Mar 07, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/3506592-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3506592-michael?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3506592-michael?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3506592-michael?shelf=religion">religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer875039301" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10891114272710617463">A solid (albeit a trifle long) history of atheism, agnosticism, secularism, and &apos;free thinkers&apos; in America. I knew some of this history, but much of it was new to me. If anything, this book has reinforced the necessity for a separation of religion and government in my mind, something that, in recent years, has faded a bit from my thinking. The Founders did not set out to create a Christian nation. Teaching evolution in schools is not something that is controversial outside the fever swamp of fun</span>
  <span id="freeText10891114272710617463" style="display:none">A solid (albeit a trifle long) history of atheism, agnosticism, secularism, and 'free thinkers' in America. I knew some of this history, but much of it was new to me. If anything, this book has reinforced the necessity for a separation of religion and government in my mind, something that, in recent years, has faded a bit from my thinking. The Founders did not set out to create a Christian nation. Teaching evolution in schools is not something that is controversial outside the fever swamp of fundamentalist Christianity. There is no place for prayer of any kind in public schools. We are not one nation 'under God.' We are one nation. Period. <br /><br />Having spent the better part of a decade studying and practicing and reading about religion, this book was a bit of a slap in the face to me, reminding me of things I once knew and believed, but have recently forgotten. I am all for religious freedom, and I think people have an immutable right to practice their faith, as well as making their truth claims in the public square with as loud a voice as they can muster. But; there is no place for faith in apparatus of government. Jefferson's wall needs to be tall and strong, especially now, at a time when there has never been greater religious diversity--as well as a growing number of 'nones' and atheists--in our country. <br /><br />A good book, and an excellent reminder. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10891114272710617463" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


