<div id="review_1517787645" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1517787645" />
    <a title="NJ Wong" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51739980-nj-wong"><img alt="NJ Wong" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1453276825p2/51739980.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1517787645?book_show_action=true">Jan 20, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="NJ Wong" class="user" itemprop="url" name="NJ Wong" href="/user/show/51739980-nj-wong">NJ Wong</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780805074420" href="/book/show/1635636.Freethinkers">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51739980-nj-wong?shelf=shelfari-favorites">shelfari-favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1517787645" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12908652872293480630">Reading this book reminded me of the book &quot;Doubt: A History&quot; by Jennifer Michael Hecht. Both books are about the history of free thought, but Susan Jacoby&apos;s book is intensely focused on the happenings in the US, while Jennifer Hecht&apos;s book has a global scope. Both books are equally delightful.<br/><br/>The strangest thing about the US today is its great religious (read Christian) fervour, sometimes bordering the intensity of that of Islamic countries. Yet, the US is a country founded on secular terms, and</span>
  <span id="freeText12908652872293480630" style="display:none">Reading this book reminded me of the book "Doubt: A History" by Jennifer Michael Hecht. Both books are about the history of free thought, but Susan Jacoby's book is intensely focused on the happenings in the US, while Jennifer Hecht's book has a global scope. Both books are equally delightful.<br /><br />The strangest thing about the US today is its great religious (read Christian) fervour, sometimes bordering the intensity of that of Islamic countries. Yet, the US is a country founded on secular terms, and whose founders took extreme measures to ensure that no single religion is to be favoured over another. Yet, in 2013, US politicians in the Republican Party go all out to prove that they are "more Christian" than their opponents in their campaign hustlings! As most scientists are non-believers (once you understand the science, the explanations offered by the Christian Bible of why things are read like fairy tales), you don't see them elected within the Republican Party (unless they feign fanatical religiosity - of the Christian kind of course). <br /><br />This book offers a good narrative of how this had come about. However, because it was published in 2004, this meant that it could not cover new developments in the US like New Atheism and the Tea Party. Perhaps her more recent book, "The Age of American Unreason" will cover this in more detail. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12908652872293480630" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


