    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3620154420" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3620154420" />
    <a title="Don" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4722031-don"><img alt="Don" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3620154420?book_show_action=true">May 07, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Don" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Don" href="/user/show/4722031-don">Don</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3620154420" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9689541710155031777">     What Susan Jacoby calls “one of the greatest unresolved paradoxes of American history” has been one of  the mystifying elements of my own life as an American. I grew up feeling patriotic pride in my nation and its grounding in individual freedoms and its welcome of the &quot;tired, poor, huddled masses yearning to breathe free,&quot; a nation that insisted on religious freedom and our First Amendment rights. I have long been mystified that many others didn’t see things that way, waging a continuing b</span>
  <span id="freeText9689541710155031777" style="display:none">     What Susan Jacoby calls “one of the greatest unresolved paradoxes of American history” has been one of  the mystifying elements of my own life as an American. I grew up feeling patriotic pride in my nation and its grounding in individual freedoms and its welcome of the "tired, poor, huddled masses yearning to breathe free," a nation that insisted on religious freedom and our First Amendment rights. I have long been mystified that many others didn’t see things that way, waging a continuing battle to assert the fundamentally Christian character of the nation.<br /> Jacoby’s history is book-ended by over-arching summaries which resonated deeply with me and define the frame for the contents of the book:<br /> From the Introduction: "It is one of the greatest unresolved paradoxes of American history that religion has come to occupy such an important place in the communal psyche and public life of a nation founded on the separation of church and state. The tension between secularism and religion was present at America's creation; a secular government, independent of all religious sects, was seen by founders of diverse private beliefs as the essential guarantor of liberty of conscience. The descendants of passionate religious dissenters, who had fled the church-state establishments of the Old World in order to worship God in a multiplicity of ways, were beholden to a godless constitution. From the beginning of the republic this irony-laden and profoundly creative relationship produced a mixture of gratitude and unease on the part of its beneficiaries."<br /> From the concluding chapter: “For the past four decades, the militant religious right has mounted a tireless assault on separation of church and state - a principle deeply inculcated in though seldom reflected upon by a public that takes religious freedom for granted. For the religiously correct, it is not enough for Americans to believe, as they always have and do today, that government interference with religion is a bad thing. The public must also be persuaded that religious interference with government is a good thing - that it is not interference at all but the beneficient and harmonious manifestation of God's blessings upon America."<br /> Between the bookends, Jacoby provides an interesting and informative recounting of many of the champions of the freethinking side of this ongoing tension in American society and their principal opponents who have carried the argument against freethinking, secular government through our history. As we continue these struggles over the roles of church and state at the political heart of The American governmental system, Jacoby’s book serves well to remind and inform us of the ongoing and evolving nature of the arguments and of the political coalitions carrying them throughout our history. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9689541710155031777" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

