    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3793646644" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3793646644" />
    <a title="Jeffrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/124810-jeffrey"><img alt="Jeffrey" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3793646644?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeffrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeffrey" href="/user/show/124810-jeffrey">Jeffrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3793646644" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16088876021114324861">I read Freethinkers shortly after it was published, and so some of my review will be asked on fuzzy memory. But the lessons from this book have staid with me. What I had seen as a conflict or tension specific to my time, I now understand as part of a long running tension between two ways of thinking that had have been part of America since its founding. This kind of historical perspective was very new to me, and having now glimpsed it I want to preach it to others.<br/><br/>And while I learned some things</span>
  <span id="freeText16088876021114324861" style="display:none">I read Freethinkers shortly after it was published, and so some of my review will be asked on fuzzy memory. But the lessons from this book have staid with me. What I had seen as a conflict or tension specific to my time, I now understand as part of a long running tension between two ways of thinking that had have been part of America since its founding. This kind of historical perspective was very new to me, and having now glimpsed it I want to preach it to others.<br /><br />And while I learned some things which I thought were specific to my time had been very long running, I also learned the opposite lesson. For example, when the US Postal Service was first established, mail was delivered seven days a week. The removal of Sunday mail service was an early battle won by the non-secularists. Until reading Freethinkers, I had tacitly assumed that mail was never delivered on Sundays. The example is important for any number of reasons, but it also shows the importance of a historical perspective.<br /><br />Again, it’s been a while since I read this, but I recall finding it a delight to read for its clarity, directness, and quality of giving just the right amount of information for non-historians. <br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16088876021114324861" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


